irror of reality or as a unified science. How should we understand economics and, more broadly, the organization and disorganization of material life? In this book, international scholars from anthropology and economics adopt a rhetorical perspective in order to make sense of material life and the theories about it. Re-examining central problems in the two fields and using ethnographic and historical examples, they explore the intersections between these disciplines, contrast their methods and epistemologies, and show how a rhetorical approach offers a new mode of analysis while drawing on established contributions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEconomic anthropology. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric). 0aRhetoricxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBird-David, Nurit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrier, James G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgel, Metin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarr, Asaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenzer, LaRay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGudeman, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGudeman, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuyer, Jane I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlamer, Arjo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilberg, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliven, Ruben George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwedberg, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https